%Fonts Dialog%
%Fonts Dialog%
%fonts_dialog%
The Fonts dialog allows you to interactively change the fonts and
labels of some objects on the screen.  You may change the font
for entire "classes" of objects, such as all the push buttons.  
You may also change individual objects separately; for example,
you may change the font of only the Read button in the Main Window.
You may also use this dialog to change the text (or label) on
a particular interface item such as a menu or button.

The scrolling area at the top of the window lists all the 
currently available fonts.  The Font(s): field displays the
font currently selected in the scrolling area.  You may type
a font name in this field directly if you prefer. The scrolling
area in the center of the window displays sample text in the
currently selected font.

Use the toggles in the Set Mode: area to specify the type
of action you want to perform.

        - Fonts: Interactive is used to assign fonts to 
          specific interface objects, such as a single push button.

        - Fonts: Object Type is used to assign fonts to entire
          classes of objects, such as all push buttons or all
          menus.

        - Label Only is used to change only the text on a
          specific interface object.  For example, you can change
          the label on the Read button in the Main Window to
          "Display" instead.

        - Label and Font is used to both change the text on a
          specific interface object and to assign a new font.

If you're assigning fonts to entire classes of objects, use the
Objects: toggle buttons to specify the items to which the new
font should be applied. 

Once you've selected a font and specified a mode, click Assign.
If you're using any mode except for Object Type, the cursor 
changes to a pencil.  Click on an interface object to change
it according to the mode you're using.

If you're using Label Only or Label and Font mode, an
Input dialog appears containing the current name of the
object.  Enter a new label in the dialog and click OK.

You may click on as many objects as you wish.  When you are 
finished, click on any part of the screen NOT ASSOCIATED WITH 
Z-MAIL and the cursor will return to normal.

If you like what you've chosen, click the "Save" button.

The file from which Z-Mail retrieves settings of fonts and labels saved
in this dialog is identified by the value of the variable ~#fonts_db~var#~.
If ~#fonts_db~var#~ is not set, the default fonts file is .zmfonts in your
home directory.  When you click "Save", an Input popup displays the
current value of ~#fonts_db~var#~ and asks you whether to save the fonts and
labels there.  You may edit the file name in the Input popup to save
fonts to another file.

If you save settings to a file other than that first shown, you must
change the value of ~#fonts_db~var#~ in order for Z-Mail to use the fonts.
This value can be changed in the Variables dialog.

Unfortunately, due to the nature of the X system, you cannot reset your
fonts and labels back to their original settings.  If you wish to
revert to the original fonts and labels, you must remove the fonts file
and restart Z-Mail.  
