%Updating%
%update%
When you update a folder, the changes that you've made to the folder
since the last update are made permanent.  Deleted mail is permanently
purged from the folder and cannot be retrieved after an update.

You can only update the active folder.  To update the active folder,
you can:

  - Choose the Update item from the
    Folder menu on the ~#Main Window#~.

  - Click the Update button on the 
    ~#Main Window#~.

If new mail has arrived in the folder, Z-Mail will incorporate it
before updating.
%%

%Unpreserve%
%%<Preserve
%%

%Preserve%
After you read mail and you "update" or quit Z-Mail, unread messages
are copied back into your system mailbox and deleted messages are
removed.  Messages which have been read but not deleted may either be
held in the system mailbox or saved in your main mailbox file.

The location of your main mailbox is determined by the value of the
~#mbox~var#~ variable and is "~/mbox" by default.  This file is referred to
as the mbox file.

The variable ~#hold~var#~ determines whether messages remain in the system
mailbox or are saved to your mbox.  Normally messages are held, but
your system administrator may have configured Z-Mail to save them.

You can mark specific messages to be held in your system mailbox by
preserving" them with the Preserve menu item.  Preserved messages are
always held, even when Z-Mail has been configured to save other
messages in the mbox.

To preserve a message, select Preserve either from the Main Window
Message menu or from the right-button popup in the Message Summaries
area.  To remove the preserved mark from a message, the Unpreserve
item is used.
%%

%Next%
In the Message Display Window, selecting either the "Next" button or
the "Read Next" item from the Find menu will take you to the next
message in the folder that has neither been saved nor deleted.
%%<-shared-delete
%%

%Delete%
The Delete item of the Main Window Message menu marks as deleted all
messages whose numbers appear in the Messages: field.  Unless you have
edited the Messages: field, the numbers there are those of the selected
messages in the Message Summaries list.

In the Message Display Window, the "Delete" button marks as deleted the
message that is displayed.  The Delete item from the Message menu marks as
deleted all messages whose numbers are shown in the Messages: field.
Unless you have edited the Messages: field, the number there is the
same as that of the displayed message.
%%<-shared-delete
%%

%-shared-delete%
Selecting "Delete" may also take you to the next message in the
folder, except that the current message is deleted before advancing.
The variable ~#autoprint~var#~ must be set in order for "Delete" to
advance automatically to the next message.  It is advisable to delete
unimportant mail after reading it, as it conserves system resources
and improves the efficiency of Z-Mail.
%%

%Aliases%
%creating_aliases%
%alias_dialog%
Aliases allow you to mail to users with long addresses using short
names. For example, if you often send messages to:

    fred@fjones.com

but don't want to type this long address every time you send a
message, you may make an alias for that address.

In the Mail Aliases dialog, select the "Alias Name:" text entry field
and enter a shorter but equally meaningful name, such as:

    fred

then select the "Alias Address(es):" field and type:

    fred@fjones.com

Finally, click on the Apply button to add the new alias to the alias
list.  Now, whenever you specify

   fred

as the recipient of a message, it will be sent to fred@fjones.com.

See the Help Index entry for ~#Address Forms#~ for more details on address
formats and syntax.

If you frequently mail to a group of people, you may create an alias to
stand for the entire group.  Choose an alias name as usual and simply
place all the recipients in the "Alias Address(es):" field:

    Alias Name:  project-group
 
    Alias Address(es):  fred mary bob@jay.eng sly@baz.bitnet
 
To remove one or more aliases, select them from the list and click
Delete.
%%<Mailing to Aliases
%%

%Mailing to Aliases%
When composing a message, you may use an alias name anywhere you would
use a normal address:

    To: fred
    Subject: Alias example
    Cc: project-group
 
    (rest of letter)
 
You may send mail to aliases from the list in the Mail Aliases dialog.
Select the aliases to which you want to send from the list, then click
the "Use" button.  A new ~#Compose Window#~ opens, addressed to the
aliases you have selected.
%%<comp_alias_dialog
%%

%Using Aliases%
%comp_alias_dialog%
You may select aliases to add to the the address fields of an existing
Compose Window by selecting the "Aliases" item from the Address menu
of the ~#Compose Window#~.  This brings up the Mail Aliases dialog
with a list from which you may select aliases.

Click any of the "To", "Cc", or "Bcc" buttons to add the selected
aliases to the corresponding address fields of the message.

You may also type alias names directly into any of the address fields
in the Compose Window.
%%

