%Filters Dialog%
%filters_dialog%

To access the Filters dialog, choose Filters from the Options
menu in the Main Window.

To filter messages that contain a text pattern, click
on Filter By Pattern.  To filter messages based on
the date they were received, click Filter By Date.

The upper right hand portion of the Filters dialog
changes depending on which of these items you've 
chosen. 

If you choose Filter By Date, use the check boxes
to specify the age of message you want to filter.

If you choose Filter by Pattern, specify a pattern
in the Search Pattern: field and use the check boxes
to indicate where the pattern must be found. 

Use to pop-up menu to specify what action should
be performed on the filtered messages.  The text
field below this pop-up changes depending on which 
action you choose.

        - If you choose Save to File or Copy to File, specify 
	  the name of the file to which messages should
          be saved.

        - If you choose Save by Author or Save by
          Subject, the name of the file will be
          either the sender or the subject of the
          message.  Use the text field to specify
          the directory where these files should
          be stored.

        - If you choose Mark, messages which match
	   will become marked. To unmark messages
	   which match a filter, select Unmark.
        
        - If you choose Delete, messages which match
	   will be deleted when you update the folder. To 
	   undelete messages which match a filter, select 
	   Undelete.

       - If you choose Forward, specify the 
          e-mail address to which messages should
          be resent.

        - If you choose reply, specify the name of
          a file that contains the text of the reply.

        - If you choose Z-Script, specify the name 
          of the Z-Script function which should be invoked.

If you turn on Filter New Mail Only, only new mail
will be filtered.  If you don't turn on this box,
all the messages in your system mailbox will be 
filtered, but only when you invoke Z-Mail
with the -filter option:

        zmail -gui -filter

Finally, specify a name for the filter and click Install
to install it.  

To delete an existing filter, select its name in the 
Installed Filters list and click Delete.
%%

@@ifndef ZMAIL_BASIC
%Functions%

You may create your own Z-Script functions using
the Functions dialog, which is accessed by
choosing Functions... from the Options menu in
the Main Window.  The scrolling list at the left
displays all currently defined functions,
including Z-Mail internal functions. The text
area at the right displays the contents of the
currently selected function.  

To view any function, select it from the
list. To create your own function, click the
Clear button, enter the name of the function in
the Function Name field, and enter the text of
the function in the Function text box. When you
have finished entering the text of the function,
click Install to install it.  

To delete an installed function, select it and
click Delete. You cannot delete Z-Mail internal
functions.
