%Spell Checking%
%spelling checker%
To check the spelling of your text, click the Spell button in the
~#Search and Replace#~ dialog.  The Misspelled Words list at the right
will be filled in with possible spelling errors.  To correct a
misspelling, select the word from the list.  This word is copied to
the Search field.  Fill in the correct spelling in the Replace field,
select All Occurrences, and click Replace.

This dialog is accessed via the Search/Replace/Spell...
item from the Edit menu in the ~#Compose Window#~.

You may also invoke an external, interactive spelling
checker, if one is available to you.  To do this, you
must have the ispeller variable set to the name of the
external program. 

See the variables ~#speller#~ and ~#ispeller#~ for additional
information.
%%

%Status Bar%
The Status Bar is located at the bottom of a window and reports
abbreviated information about your mailbox.
  
In the Main Window, the Status Bar is divided into two sections.
The left side displays abbreviated output similar to that which appears in
the ~#Output Area#~. The right side displays information about
your mailbox, similar to that displayed by the ~#Folder Status List#~.
  
Status Bars in the Compose and Message Windows are each divided into
three sections: 
  
  The left-most section displays abbreviated output
  similar to that which appears in the ~#Output Area#~.
  
  The center section displays the name of the current
  folder. 
  
  The right-most section displays the status of the
  current folder.
  
You can invoke the Status Bar in the ~#Main Window#~, the
~#Compose Window#~, or the ~#Message Display Window#~ by selecting
Status Bar from the Layout menu, which is located
on the Menu Bar at the top of the window.
  
You can also invoke Status Bars by setting your main_panes,
compose_panes, and message_panes ~#variables#~.
 

%%

%Templates%
%templates_dialog%
Templates are predefined text forms that you can use when composing
outgoing mail.  The Templates dialog shows you a list of the
available prepared forms.  Select one of the forms in the list
and click the "Use" button.  A ~#Compose Window#~ will be opened with
the template inserted in the composition area, ready for your editing.

You can define your own template files.  See the ~#templates~var#~
variable for more information.

If one of the templates in your templates directory (as defined by the
~#templates~var#~ variable) is named "default", Z-Mail reads that file
into every message you compose, unless you explicitly select a
different template.
